'''Thomas William Andrews (T. Bill)''' (born 1958 in Hutchinson, Kansas) is an American [[abstract impressionist]] [[Painting|painter]] and [[author]]. He paints [[landscapes]], florals and representational and architectural pieces in the style of [[impressionism]], as well as [[Figurative art|figurative]] studies, but his primary emphasis is on extremely large-format [[action painting]] in a style reminiscent of [[Jackson Pollock]] and other painters in the [[New York School (art)|New York School]] of painting known as [[abstract expressionism]].
After serving in the U.S. Navy [[Nuclear Power]] Program, he enrolled as an undergraduate member of the [[University of Iowa Writers' Workshop]] in the mid-1980s. It was while at the Writers' Workshop that he adopted his [[nom de plume]] "T. Bill" (sometimes "T-Bill". He then received his doctorate from Yale University, writing a fictionalized memoir of his experiences at Yale entitled "Power Ties."
His [[abstract art]] painting studio is located alongside a horse meadow. His largest collection of work is at his flagship gallery in West Des Moines.<ref>[http://www.kavanaughgallery.com/T-Bill_Andrews.html Images of some of T-Bill's paintings at Kavanaugh Gallery in West Des Moines]</ref> Acquisitions at other galleries are handled by Mid-America Art Brokers of St. Louis.
==Works== * ''Power Ties'', Instantpublisher.com, 2004,{{ISBN|978-1-59196-461-2}}
